**Audit and Accountability (AU) — System-Specific for Application Audit Logs**

| Control | Implementation Owner | Implementation Description |
|---|---|---|
| AU-2 Event Logging | MyClinic — IT Administrator and ISSO | OpenMRS application logging configured per Day 48 specification; application-level audit events (patient record access, modifications, authentication) logged to CloudWatch |
| AU-3 Content of Audit Records | MyClinic — IT Administrator | Application audit records contain required fields: user identifier, timestamp, patient identifier, action type, outcome, source IP |
| AU-5 Response to Audit Logging Process Failures | MyClinic — ISSO | Alert configured in CloudWatch for logging failures; ISSO notified within 15 minutes of audit logging interruption |
| AU-8 Time Stamps | MyClinic — IT Administrator | System time synchronized with AWS NTP service; all audit records use UTC timestamp |
| AU-11 Audit Record Retention | MyClinic — ISSO | Application audit logs retained 6 years per HIPAA documentation retention requirement; retention configured in CloudWatch log group settings |

*Note on AU allocation — important distinction:* AWS CloudTrail captures all AWS API calls across the account — this is a hybrid control documented below. But the OpenMRS application audit log — who accessed which patient record — is entirely a system-specific control. CloudTrail does not record application-level access to patient data. The distinction between infrastructure audit logs (CloudTrail — hybrid) and application audit logs (CloudWatch application logging — system-specific) must be documented clearly in the SSP. Conflating them is one of the most common control coverage gaps in cloud-hosted healthcare systems.

