### Hybrid Controls — Shared Responsibility

These are the controls where AWS provides part of the implementation and MyClinic provides the rest. Both portions must be documented and both must be assessed. An assessor reviewing a hybrid control needs to understand both what was inherited and what was implemented by MyClinic.

---

**Encryption Controls — SC-28, SC-8**

| Control | AWS Portion | MyClinic Portion |
|---|---|---|
| SC-28 Protection of Information at Rest | AWS provides RDS encryption capability (AES-256 via AWS KMS); AWS provides S3 server-side encryption capability | MyClinic must enable encryption on RDS instance (not enabled by default — must be configured at creation); MyClinic must configure SSE-KMS on S3 backup bucket; MyClinic must create and manage the customer-managed KMS key; MyClinic must enable EC2 EBS volume encryption |
| SC-8 Transmission Confidentiality and Integrity | AWS provides TLS termination capability via Application Load Balancer and ACM; AWS manages the underlying TLS infrastructure | MyClinic must configure HTTPS enforcement — redirect HTTP to HTTPS; MyClinic must configure TLS 1.2 minimum in OpenMRS and Tomcat; MyClinic must obtain and maintain the TLS certificate via ACM |

*Critical documentation note:* AWS providing encryption capability is fundamentally different from encryption being enabled. An assessor who reviews SC-28 by confirming that AWS offers RDS encryption has not confirmed that the OpenMRS RDS instance is encrypted. The assessment evidence for the MyClinic portion of SC-28 is: screenshot of RDS instance showing encryption enabled; confirmation of KMS key identifier; confirmation that key is customer-managed.

---

**Logging and Monitoring Controls — AU-6, SI-4**

| Control | AWS Portion | MyClinic Portion |
|---|---|---|
| AU-6 Audit Review and Analysis | AWS provides CloudTrail for API-level logging; AWS provides CloudWatch for log aggregation and alerting capability; AWS provides GuardDuty for automated threat detection | MyClinic must configure CloudTrail to capture all regions and management events; MyClinic must create CloudWatch metric filters and alarms for security-relevant events; MyClinic must enable GuardDuty; MyClinic must configure Security Hub to aggregate findings; MyClinic must establish review process for GuardDuty findings and CloudWatch alerts |
| SI-4 Information System Monitoring | AWS provides GuardDuty, CloudTrail, Config, VPC Flow Logs capability | MyClinic must enable all monitoring services; configure alert thresholds; establish response procedures; assign personnel responsible for daily finding review |

*Documentation note:* The Day 28 Capital One breach case is directly relevant here. Capital One had GuardDuty alerts generated — the AWS portion was working. The gap was in the MyClinic-equivalent portion: the review and response process that should have acted on those alerts. Both portions of the hybrid control must be implemented for the control to be effective.

---

**Patch Management — SI-2**

| Control | AWS Portion | MyClinic Portion |
|---|---|---|
| SI-2 Flaw Remediation | AWS automatically patches RDS managed service (OS-level patches applied by AWS; minor engine patches applied automatically if configured); AWS patches the underlying hypervisor and host infrastructure | MyClinic must patch the OpenMRS application when new releases address security vulnerabilities; MyClinic must patch the EC2 Ubuntu OS (not automatic — MyClinic must apply OS patches); MyClinic must patch Apache Tomcat; MyClinic must update OpenMRS dependencies when vulnerability patches are released |

*Documentation note:* The automatic RDS patching from AWS covers the database engine. It does not cover the OpenMRS application running on EC2, the EC2 operating system, or Apache Tomcat. The SI-2 hybrid allocation makes this boundary explicit — an assessor looking for OS patch evidence should look at EC2 patch history, not just confirm that RDS is managed by AWS.

