## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

While working through the hybrid encryption allocation today I returned to the **2019 Capital One breach** — covered on Day 33 from the asset inventory perspective — but today specifically through the hybrid control allocation failure lens.

Capital One's breach involved a Server Side Request Forgery vulnerability that allowed an attacker to query the AWS EC2 instance metadata service and retrieve temporary IAM credentials. The attacker then used those credentials to access S3 buckets containing customer data.

The relevant allocation detail: AWS provided all the security tools that could have detected and mitigated this breach — GuardDuty was available, WAF was available, IAM permission boundaries were available. These were all hybrid controls where AWS provided the capability and Capital One was responsible for the configuration and monitoring portions.

The post-incident analysis found that Capital One had not configured WAF rules to block the specific type of SSRF request used in the attack, had not configured IAM permission boundaries that would have restricted the blast radius of compromised instance credentials, and had GuardDuty alerts that were not acted on promptly.

Every one of those gaps was in the MyClinic-equivalent portion of a hybrid control. AWS provided the capability. The system-specific configuration and monitoring portions were not adequately implemented.

The Task S-3 allocation documentation for hybrid controls — specifically the SC-7 WAF configuration and SI-4 monitoring review portions — directly addresses the pattern of failure that the Capital One breach illustrates. The point of documenting both portions of a hybrid control is to make the MyClinic-responsible portion visible and accountable, so it cannot be assumed away.

